&lt;p&gt;If you’ve ever watched fresh rain bead up and roll off a brand-new deck, you’ve seen the surface behave like a waxed car. It looks healthy and waterproof, right up to the moment you try to stain it and the finish flashes unevenly, blotches, or peels in sheets. That isn’t a failure of the stain. It’s the result of mill glaze—an artifact from planing at the mill where knives compress fibers, heat softens lignin, and resins are smeared across the surface, creating a semi-burnished shell. The surest fix is precise, methodical deck sanding. Not a token pass, but a controlled removal of that top layer so finish can mechanically anchor and wick into pores as the manufacturer intended.&lt;/p&gt;</summary><media:content url="https://blog.equalle.com/images/brand/17.webp" medium="image"/><media:content url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding/cards/facebook/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding.jpg" medium="image"/><media:thumbnail url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding/cards/facebook/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding.jpg"/><enclosure url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding/cards/facebook/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding.jpg" type="image/jpeg"/><media:content url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding/cards/instagram/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding.jpg" medium="image"/><media:thumbnail url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding/cards/instagram/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding-deck-sanding.jpg"/><enclosure url="https://blog.equalle.com/posts/2026/01/14/remove-mill-glaze-from-new-deck-boards-by-sanding